ARCHITECTURE

phantom-auth is a FastAPI service that terminates user authentication
in front of phantom-daemon. Every dashboard request from the SPA hits
auth-service first; only authenticated, role-checked requests reach
the daemon over its Unix domain socket.


Position in the stack
---------------------

  Browser (dashboard SPA)
       │
       │  HTTPS
       ▼
  nginx (TLS termination)
       │
       │  HTTP
       ▼
  auth-service ── /auth/*  login, MFA, sessions, users, audit
               ── /api/*   authenticated reverse proxy to daemon
       │
       │  UDS (unix:///var/run/phantom/daemon.sock)
       ▼
  phantom-daemon

  No daemon endpoint is reachable without a valid auth-service
  token. The daemon does not implement authentication itself.


Process model
-------------

  Single Python process, FastAPI under uvicorn.

  All long-lived state lives on app.state, populated by the lifespan
  context manager (auth_service/app.py:lifespan) in five phases:

    1. Load configuration from environment      (config.py)
    2. Load Ed25519 signing keypair from disk   (crypto/keys.py)
    3. Validate auth.db exists                  (db/repository.py)
    4. Build httpx client to daemon (UDS or HTTP)
    5. Build in-memory rate limiter             (middleware/rate_limit.py)

  Startup failure is critical and fatal: sys.exit(1). The service
  refuses to run with partially-initialised state.


Persistence layer
-----------------

  A single SQLite file at $AUTH_DB_DIR/auth.db, opened with
  PRAGMA journal_mode = WAL and PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON.

  Schema (auth_service/db/schema.sql):

    users                id, username, password_hash, role,
                         totp_secret, timestamps.
    totp_backup_codes    per-user one-time backup codes (hashed).
    sessions             id, user_id, token_jti, token_hash,
                         issued_at, expires_at, last_activity_at,
                         revoked.
    audit_log            every login attempt, MFA verification,
                         password change, user-management action,
                         and proxy request. Append-only.

  The file is created once by tools/bootstrap.py during initial
  setup; the runtime never creates or migrates schema. If the file
  is missing, startup aborts.

  Connections are per-request, not pooled. _DBMiddleware
  (auth_service/app.py) opens a fresh sqlite3 connection on every
  inbound request, stores it on request.state.db, and closes it
  after the response. This eliminates the threading hazards that
  arise from sharing a single sqlite3 connection across asyncio
  workers — a real bug fixed in v1.1.0.


Authentication flow
-------------------

  1. POST /auth/login            username + password → either:
                                   - "needs_mfa": short-lived MFA
                                     token (120s default) when TOTP
                                     is enrolled, or
                                   - access token + session record.
                                 Both branches write to audit_log.

  2. POST /auth/mfa/verify       MFA token + TOTP code → access
                                 token + session.

  3. POST /auth/totp/backup      MFA token + backup code → access
                                 token. Backup code is consumed.

  4. POST /auth/logout           Revokes the active session by JTI.

  5. GET  /auth/me               Returns current user + role.

  Access tokens default to 24h. Sessions also enforce a 30-minute
  inactivity timeout — every authenticated call updates
  last_activity_at; idle sessions auto-revoke on the next access
  attempt.


Authorization
-------------

  middleware/auth.py:require_auth
  Steps:

    1. Extract Bearer token from the Authorization header.
    2. Verify Ed25519 signature, decode payload.
    3. Check token_type == "access".
    4. Look up the session by jti; reject if missing or revoked.
    5. Check that stored token_hash matches sha256 of the raw token
       — prevents reuse if a JTI leaks but the token does not.
    6. Check inactivity timeout; revoke if exceeded.
    7. Update last_activity_at.

  Two roles:

    admin        /auth/me, /logout, /auth/password/* (own password),
                 /auth/totp/* (own TOTP), and the /api/* proxy.
    superadmin   Everything admin can do, plus /auth/users/* (create,
                 list, delete, force-change password) and /auth/audit
                 (read audit log).

  Role enforcement uses require_superadmin — a thin-wrapper around
  require_auth that asserts payload.role == "superadmin"


Cryptography
------------

  JWT — Ed25519, manual implementation (crypto/jwt.py)
    No extra dependency. Header.Payload.Signature with base64url
    parts. Algorithm is pinned to "EdDSA"; any other alg in the
    header fails verification.

    The signing keypair lives on disk as two 64-char hex files in
    $AUTH_SECRETS_DIR (mounted as Docker secrets in production):
    one for the private (signing) key, one for the public (verify)
    key. Both are length- and format-validated at load time.

  Passwords — Argon2id (crypto/password.py via PyNaCl)
    Default OPSLIMIT/MEMLIMIT from libsodium. Hash + verify only;
    no parameter tuning is exposed.

  TOTP — RFC 6238, standard library (crypto/totp.py)
    HMAC-SHA1, 6 digits, 30-second period, 160-bit secret. Emits
    otpauth:// URIs for authenticator-app enrollment. Backup codes
    are 8 codes of 8 characters each, stored hashed (one-time use).


Reverse proxy
-------------

  routes/proxy.py owns /api/{path:path}. Every method
  (GET POST PUT DELETE PATCH HEAD OPTIONS) is forwarded.

  Per-request flow:
    1. Apply require_auth (unauthenticated requests never reach the
       daemon).
    2. Build the target URL from config.proxy_base_url + path +
       query.
    3. Resolve user_id from username for audit context.
    4. Read the request body; reject with 413 if larger than
       AUTH_PROXY_MAX_BODY.
    5. Strip Host / Authorization / Content-Length /
       Transfer-Encoding from forwarded headers.
    6. Forward via httpx AsyncClient (UDS transport in production).
    7. Audit-log the request: method, path, query, response status.
    8. Pass the response back, preserving content-type while
       stripping length/encoding headers (uvicorn re-computes them).
    9. JSON responses are re-encoded as JSONResponse; binary
       responses pass through raw — fixed in a recent revision so
       endpoints that return tarballs (backup export) work
       end-to-end.


Rate limiting
-------------

  middleware/rate_limit.py:RateLimiter — in-memory sliding window
  per source IP, threadsafe via a single Lock. Default: 5 attempts
  per 60 seconds. Used only on /auth/login; everything else relies
  on the session/token model.

  Successful login resets the counter for the IP.


Configuration
-------------

  All settings are environment-driven, loaded once at startup into
  an immutable AuthConfig (config.py — frozen=True, slots=True):

    AUTH_HOST / AUTH_PORT        0.0.0.0:8443 default
    AUTH_PROXY_URL               unix:///var/run/phantom/daemon.sock
                                 (or http://...). UDS in production.
    AUTH_DB_DIR                  /var/lib/phantom/auth
    AUTH_SECRETS_DIR             /run/secrets  (Docker secrets path)
    AUTH_TOKEN_LIFETIME          86400  (24h access token)
    AUTH_INACTIVITY_TIMEOUT      1800   (30m sliding session)
    AUTH_MFA_TOKEN_LIFETIME      120    (2m MFA token)
    AUTH_TOTP_SETUP_LIFETIME     300    (5m enrollment QR window)
    AUTH_PROXY_MAX_BODY          67108864 (64 MB — backup export)
    AUTH_RATE_LIMIT_WINDOW/MAX   60 / 5


Error envelope
--------------

  Every response — success or failure — uses a stable shape:

    Success:  { "ok": true,  "data": ... }
    Error:    { "ok": false, "error_code": "..." }

  Error codes are stable strings (UNAUTHORIZED, TOKEN_EXPIRED,
  SESSION_INACTIVE, MFA_REQUIRED, BODY_TOO_LARGE, …). HTTP status
  codes remain meaningful, but the SPA branches on error_code.

  Three layers:
    auth_service/errors.py        Python-side hierarchy (AuthError →
                                  AuthSecretsError, AuthTokenError,
                                  AuthCredentialsError, …).
    ApiException                  HTTP-aware exception carrying
                                  status + error_code.
    app.py:_register_error_handlers
                                  Maps everything (including
                                  FastAPI's RequestValidationError)
                                  into the envelope.


Bootstrap
---------

  tools/setup.sh + tools/bootstrap.py is the one-time setup. Run
  once per host, builds an image + ad-hoc container that:

    1. Generates an Ed25519 keypair via PyNaCl SigningKey.
    2. Writes signing/verify keys as 64-char hex files into
       $AUTH_SECRETS_DIR.
    3. Creates auth.db with the full schema (kept in sync with
       auth_service/db/schema.sql).
    4. Generates a 32-character random password for the initial
       admin user.
    5. Hashes it with Argon2id and inserts the user with role
       'superadmin'.
    6. Prints the initial credentials once. They are never
       persisted in plaintext.

  After bootstrap, the runtime container only opens the
  pre-existing DB and pre-existing keys. It never creates them.


Container shape
---------------

  Dockerfile         python:3.12-slim + libsodium23 +
                     requirements.txt. CMD runs
                     `python -m auth_service`. No source COPY here
                     — the production package built by
                     scripts/packager.py lays the source into the
                     daemon checkout (see DISTRIBUTION).
  docker-compose.yml Mounts the Ed25519 keypair as Docker secrets,
                     restart: unless-stopped. Every environment
                     default is set explicitly so deployments can
                     audit them at a glance.

  The runtime container does not have write access to auth.db. That
  path is owned by host-side bootstrap tooling.


Source layout
-------------

  auth_service/
    __init__.py           __version__ — single source of truth
    __main__.py           uvicorn entry
    app.py                FastAPI factory + lifespan + middleware
    config.py             env-driven AuthConfig
    audit.py              audit_log helper
    errors.py             exception hierarchy
    models.py             pydantic request/response types
    crypto/
      jwt.py              Ed25519 JWT encode + decode
      keys.py             Ed25519 key load + validate
      password.py         Argon2id hash + verify
      totp.py             RFC 6238 + backup codes
    db/
      schema.sql          auth.db DDL
      connection.py       open_auth_db helper
      repository.py       AuthDB — every query
    middleware/
      auth.py             require_auth + require_superadmin
      rate_limit.py       sliding window limiter
    routes/
      __init__.py         router registration
      proxy.py            /api/* reverse proxy
      auth/
        __init__.py       /auth router prefix
        login.py          /login, /mfa/verify, /totp/backup
        session.py        /logout, /me
        password.py       /password/verify, /password/change
        totp.py           /totp/setup, /totp/confirm, /totp/disable
        users.py          /users (superadmin)
        audit.py          /audit (superadmin)
        _helpers.py       shared route helpers
